<dl id="n12112o"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12112o">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12112o"> 112(o)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> kistvaen <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n12112o"><li>FW 5.31 </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/lexa.htm#n12112o">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/l39a.htm#n12112o">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n12112o">MS BL 47471a-4v</ms> </li><li>JJA 44:048 <a name="a11d" href="../../ff/fdra/ada.htm#a11d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/a/a11d.htm#n12112o">Draft: I.1&sect;1.1</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">S. Tugean&apos;s key is preserved in the church. The P. on the last Sunday in June is very famous. Near the windmill is a small dolmen, or rather a kistvaen, the coverer of which has been lifted and propped on small stones. This was used by lepers to lie in, expecting a cure. <small> S. Baring-Gould, <a name="SBGB" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SBGB"><cite title="source">Brittany</cite></a> (1921) 38</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: kistvaen: a cist, a stone sepulchure; esp. one of upright stones with a further stone placed horizontally on top.</mm> </dd></dl>
